<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06072029 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06072029 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Associated Press; FAMILY FAREWELL -- An Iraqi mother, left,waves as she chases a Kuwaiti bus carrying away her son, after Kuwaitisoldiers arrested him at a checkpoint near Safwan, Iraq.  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  TURKEY; GOVERNMENT; SUPPORT; CHANGE; PRESIDENT; ASSAULT; END; MIDEAST; IRAQ;KUWAIT; US; WORLD; SAUDI-ARABIA; WAR; MILITARY; DEFENSE  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  The Iraqi opposition gained important political support Monday as Turkeyannounced that high officials of its government, in a major policy reversal,have met with Iraq's Kurdish leaders, who are attempting to overthrowPresident Saddam Hussein.;    The announcement from Ankara by TurkishPresident Turgut Ozal came as more than 20 Iraqi opposition groups opened athree-day meeting here aimed to forge a unified way to topple the governmentin Baghdad.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  TURKEY DEALS BLOW TO IRAQ BY MEETING WITHKURDSANTI-SADDAM ORGANIZATIONS MEET TO PLAN OVERTHROW  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  War in the GulfSee also related stories on pages 1A, 6A-8A in this sectionMercury News wire services contributed to this report.  </MEMO><TEXT>     Ozal, who had pledged as recently as mid-January that Turkey would fight toprevent creation of an independent Kurdish state in north Iraq, noted Mondaythat other countries, including Britain and France, have been meeting withKurdish leaders and that Turkey now has more at stake in the region.;    &quot;Weneed to keep friendly ties with them,&quot; he told journalists, the AssociatedPress reported. &quot;If we become enemies with them, others will use it againstus.&quot;;    Ozal gave no details of the substance of weekend talks in Ankarabetween Turkish Foreign Ministry and intelligence officials and Kurdishguerrilla leaders Jalal Talabani, of the Patriotic Union of Kurdistan, andMohsin Dezayee, representing the Kurdish Democratic Party.;    Dezayee saidhere Monday Turkey had agreed that Iraq should have a democratic regime andthat Iraqi Kurds should enjoy independent national rights -- or at leastwide-ranging autonomy -- within Iraq.;    For more than 60 years, Turkishgovernments have refused to talk to independence-minded Kurds.;    Fightingreportedly intensified in several areas in Iraq Monday, according to accountsby opposition sources that could not be independently verified. Oppositionleaders here claimed that 60,000 Iraqi troops had surrendered or defected andthat half the pro-Saddam units in northern Iraq had collapsed.;    TaqiMudaressi, leader of a Shiite opposition movement based in Tehran, chargedthat Iraqi troops have killed or wounded 500 people in Karbala, a Shiite holycity, which was taken over by insurgents last week. Republican Guards are&quot;ruthlessly and indiscriminately shelling&quot; Karbala, he told reporters here.&quot;They're massacring the people.&quot;;    Government news media in Baghdad saidMonday that Republican Guard members have retaken Karbala after several daysof fierce combat, the Associated Press reported.;    There was no independentconfirmation of opposition claims here of vast defections and surrenders amongtroops in northern Iraq. But, if true, the purported collapse of the 33rd and36th Divisions, following that of the 24th Division last week, would representthe loss of half of Baghdad's forces believed stationed in the mountainousnorth.;    Kurdish spokesmen said their forces have taken control of a widesection of northeastern Iraq running 150 miles north to south and 50 mileseast to west at some points and including more than two dozen towns and citiesand the vital Dokan and Darbandikhan dams near the Iranian border.;    AlsoMonday, U.S. military officials said that Iraq will turn over the bodies of 14allied servicemen killed in the Persian Gulf war.;    The remains werescheduled to be flown from Baghdad to Dhahran, Saudi Arabia, today, a militaryspokesmen said.;    Officials of the U.S. Central Command said the bodies hadnot yet been identified, nor did the officials have a breakdown ofnationalities or branches of service.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Washington Post  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Beirut, Lebanon  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910312  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Tuesday  </DAY><MONTH>  March  </MONTH><PG.COL>  6A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  579  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Tuesday March 12, 199100072029,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>